[
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/1htvSWFM17xMqT1cgl7wWwhw/Combustion_reaction_of_methane.jpg\">Combustion_reaction_of_methane.jpg</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/1htvSWFM17xMqT1cgl7wWwhw/Combustion_reaction_of_methane.jpg\" title=\"Combustion_reaction_of_methane.jpg\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/1htvSWFM17xMqT1cgl7wWwhw/Combustion_reaction_of_methane.jpg\"></a></div>",
        "id": 226223801,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613187127
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275920\">@John Baez</span> (and anyone else who is reading) I had an idea that I thought you might like or have helpful feedback on. If P and Q are Petri nets, then I think a sort of chemical recipe can be described as a symmetric monoidal functor</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>P</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R: FP \\to FQ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>where F gives the free commutative monoidal category on each Petri net. The idea is that the places of Q are all the different chemicals you're working with and the transitions of Q give all relevant reactions between those chemicals. Then P is a Petri net whose places represent macroscale quantities of chemicals and whose transitions represent steps in your chemical recipe. For example Q could contain the reaction in the image above as a transition and P could contain a transition which mixes one mole of methane with 2 moles of oxygen to produce one mole of carbon dioxide and two moles of water.</p>",
        "id": 226223806,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613187144
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Then the functor R would map the place representing on mole of CH4 to the making of Q which has about 6.02 x 10^23 tokens in the place representing CH4.</p>",
        "id": 226224009,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613187468
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>And the step in the recipe, represented by the transition combining one mole of methane with two moles of oxygen, could get mapped to one mole of the transition instances in Q.</p>",
        "id": 226224098,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613187589
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>...and the rest of the data of R is determined similarly, making sure that everything is symmetric monoidal.</p>",
        "id": 226224152,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613187624
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I didn't describe this in my example but some features of this approach is that one step in the recipe could get mapped to (a sum of) a sequence of chemical reactions in Q. Maybe this is something like a mechanism? Also the firing sequences of P could represent steps which must be performed in parallel.</p>",
        "id": 226224240,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613187742
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My question is if this really represents things that chemists really do. So if there are any chemists reading then lmk :)</p>",
        "id": 226224272,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613187824
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess that the absurd numbers of tokens in Q is probably impractical for most purposes...</p>",
        "id": 226224562,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613188262
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also this relates to <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276438\">@Fabrizio Genovese</span>'s ideas about extensions of Petri nets. This is an example of an extension in the sense you've been exploring I believe i.e. functorial semantics from the category of executions of a net.</p>",
        "id": 226224640,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613188352
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Are there any transitions in these Petri nets?</p>",
        "id": 226228250,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1613194188
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Lots! In Q they represent chemical reactions and in P they represent steps in your recipe. I should draw some pictures to explain better... maybe tomorrow.</p>",
        "id": 226232531,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613202090
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276037\">Jade Master</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229156-practice.3A-applied.20ct/topic/Chemical.20Recipes.20as.20Functors/near/226224009\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Then the functor R would map the place representing on mole of CH4 to the making of Q which has about 6.02 x 10^23 tokens in the place representing CH4.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I'd refine this a bit: If you are going micro-to-macro, probably what you want to really describe is a functor that maps a Petri net to a stochastic net</p>",
        "id": 226237017,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1613209854
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I never really tackled stochastic nets yet, but the criticism that all chemists move when we do Petri nets is that the quantities are too big to make them useful in practice. So what you want is a way to extract a system of differential equations from the net, that you can numerically plot</p>",
        "id": 226237025,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1613209910
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I should also mention that the equation attached to a stochastic net is called the \"Master Equation\", you may interpret this as a sign if you like <span aria-label=\"grinning\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f600\" role=\"img\" title=\"grinning\">:grinning:</span></p>",
        "id": 226237071,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1613209948
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's actually macro to micro...but you're right this would make more sense with some stochasticisty. The problem is that I don't know a correct categorical operational semantics for stochastic nets. Do chemists ever do discrete simulations, maybe when the reactions are on a very small scale (maybe something happening inside a single cell)</p>",
        "id": 226251079,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613231403
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Probably those discrete simulations are still stochastic.</p>",
        "id": 226251319,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613231656
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_chemistry\">https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artificial_chemistry</a> I think I've described an artificial chemistry</p>",
        "id": 226254472,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613234850
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hi, Jade!   It's weird - I was talking to Evan Patterson and others about this sort of map</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>P</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> R : FP \\to FQ </annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>in our discussion last Thursday, because it came up in something Evan was doing.  But he was doing something else with these maps.</p>\n<p>One cool thing is that these maps are more or less morphisms in the <em>Kleisli category</em> of the monad coming from the adjunction</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">i</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> F : \\mathsf{Petri} \\to \\mathsf{CommMonCat},</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">r</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">i</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">M</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span></span></span></span><br>\n<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mo>:</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">P</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">r</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">i</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> U : \\mathsf{CommMonCat} \\to \\mathsf{Petri} .</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">M</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">e</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">r</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">i</span></span><span class=\"mord\">.</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 226255264,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613235787
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh yes true, I see that.</p>",
        "id": 226255689,
        "sender_full_name": "Jade Master",
        "timestamp": 1613236258
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>They would be morphisms in the Kleisli category of the monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span> if <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{CommMonCat}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">m</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">M</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">o</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">n</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">a</span><span class=\"mord mathsf\">t</span></span></span></span></span> were the category of algebras of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>.    We've never answered this question, and it's a good pure math problem.</p>",
        "id": 226255695,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613236264
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Anyway, these morphisms you're talking about are good things <em>regardless</em> of whether Petri nets are exactly the same as algebras of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi><mi>F</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U F</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 226255725,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613236315
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I hadn't thought of how <em>you</em> are wanting to use them: as a way to scale up the number of tokens in a Petri net.</p>",
        "id": 226255796,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613236366
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The kind of example I got excited about was a bit different.</p>",
        "id": 226255816,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613236405
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>For example, oxidation of sugar in a cell can be described as this reaction:</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>12</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><mn>6</mn><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\mathrm{C}_6\\mathrm{H}_{12}\\mathrm{O}_6              +    6\\mathrm{O}_2  \\to 6\\mathrm{CO}_2    +    6 \\mathrm{H}_2\\mathrm{O}                 </annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">C</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">H</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">O</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">6</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">O</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">6</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">O</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">6</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">H</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">O</span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>However, in reality this is just a summary of a reaction with many more steps and many intermediate chemicals!</p>\n<p>We could describe this fact using a map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>P</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R : FP \\to FQ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> is a simple Petri net and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span> is a complicated one.</p>",
        "id": 226256327,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613236939
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The single reaction (transition) I wrote above would be mapped to a morphism composed of many reactions.</p>",
        "id": 226256353,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613236998
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Evan had other nice examples of maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>P</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R: F P \\to F Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 226256457,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613237114
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So I think your idea of - I'll call them \"Kleisli morphisms between Petri nets\" - could be pretty generally useful.</p>",
        "id": 226256464,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613237129
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229156-practice.3A-applied.20ct/topic/Chemical.20Recipes.20as.20Functors/near/226255695\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>We've never answered this question, and it's a good pure math problem.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Is the question \"Is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span></span></span></span> monadic?\" or something else?</p>",
        "id": 226256642,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1613237334
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>On your other question:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The problem is that I don't know a correct categorical operational semantics for stochastic nets.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"275965\">@Evan Patterson</span> is trying to work that out.  I've wanted to do it for a while, and I think I know roughly how it works, but I didn't have a student who wanted to work on that.     <span aria-label=\"upside down\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f643\" role=\"img\" title=\"upside down\">:upside_down:</span>   </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Do chemists ever do discrete simulations, maybe when the reactions are on a very small scale (maybe something happening inside a single cell).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think so: things work differently when you have small numbers of tokens.  But the people who <em>really</em> do these stochastic simulations of Petri nets are biologists describing the interactions of organisms - population biologists.  There small numbers of tokens can be <em>very</em> important.</p>\n<p>This is a very good how-to book on this stuff:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Darren James Wilkinson, <em>Stochastic Modelling for Systems Biology</em>, Taylor and Francis, New York, 2006.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 226256781,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613237498
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229156-practice.3A-applied.20ct/topic/Chemical.20Recipes.20as.20Functors/near/226256327\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>For example, oxidation of sugar in a cell can be described as this reaction:</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>12</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><mn>6</mn><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\mathrm{C}_6\\mathrm{H}_{12}\\mathrm{O}_6              +    6\\mathrm{O}_2  \\to 6\\mathrm{CO}_2    +    6 \\mathrm{H}_2\\mathrm{O}                 </annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">C</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">H</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">1</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">O</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">6</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">O</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">6</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">C</span><span class=\"mord mathrm\">O</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">6</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">H</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.30110799999999993em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">O</span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>However, in reality this is just a summary of a reaction with many more steps and many intermediate chemicals!</p>\n<p>We could describe this fact using a map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>P</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R : FP \\to FQ</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span> where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> is a simple Petri net and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8777699999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span> is a complicated one.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Well, this is exactly why in \"Petri nets are monoids\" morphisms of Petri nets aren't a couple of functions on places/transitions, but a function on places and a <em>homomorphism</em> of multisets on transitions</p>",
        "id": 226267167,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1613250237
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The idea is that those morphism are <em>simulations</em>, that are indeed the relevant concept of morphism when you are doing Petri nets in automata theory. A morphism of Petri net is that sense is precisely intended as being able to \"Compress/summarize\" many transitions into one</p>",
        "id": 226267244,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1613250300
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, I was going to add that Montanari and Meseguer consider this sort of morphism.  I didn't like it when I was trying to understand the category of Petri nets, because it's not the \"obvious\" or \"basic\" sort of map between Petri nets: it involves a mix of syntax and semantics.  But now that I understand <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2101.04238\">categories of nets</a>, I'm a lot more interested in this more general notion of morphism!</p>",
        "id": 226271691,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613254237
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By the way, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276037\">@Jade Master</span>, here's another way to think about \"chemical recipes\".   Thanks to your work there's a concept of \"real Petri net\" where a transition can use any real number amount of something, like:</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mn>0.3</mn><mtext> liters of water</mtext><mo>+</mo><mn>0.4</mn><mtext> kilograms of flour</mtext><mo>→</mo><mn>1</mn><mtext> loaf of bread</mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> 0.3 \\text{ liters of water} + 0.4 \\text{ kilograms of flour} \\to 1 \\text{ loaf of bread} </annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.77777em;vertical-align:-0.08333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span><span class=\"mord\">3</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\"> liters of water</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8888799999999999em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span><span class=\"mord\">4</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\"> kilograms of flour</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mord text\"><span class=\"mord\"> loaf of bread</span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>And thanks to your work there's a functor from the category of Petri nets to the category of real Petri nets.</p>",
        "id": 226271927,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613254447
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So, you can take an ordinary Petri net describing chemical reactions, like this:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/qz8M3eBb3QwPRoCBkTNLWcNL/Combustion_reaction_of_methane.jpg\">Combustion_reaction_of_methane.jpg</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/qz8M3eBb3QwPRoCBkTNLWcNL/Combustion_reaction_of_methane.jpg\" title=\"Combustion_reaction_of_methane.jpg\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/qz8M3eBb3QwPRoCBkTNLWcNL/Combustion_reaction_of_methane.jpg\"></a></div>",
        "id": 226272025,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613254582
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>then convert it to a real Petri net where the numbers represent <em>moles</em>, and then \"scale it up or down\" by any constant factor.</p>",
        "id": 226272034,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613254615
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There should also be a functor from Petri nets to real Petri nets where \"carbon\" gets mapped to \"12 grams\" because a mole of carbon weighs 12 grams, oxygen gets mapped to \"16 grams\", and so on.  Then we'd get a real Petri net where chemicals are measured according to mass!</p>",
        "id": 226272195,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613254819
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(Above I'm guessing that for any number <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span> there's an endofunctor on the category of real Petri nets where we rescale the amount of all species involved in any transition by multiplying it by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">x</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span></span></span></span>.)</p>",
        "id": 226272209,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1613254907
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229156-practice.3A-applied.20ct/topic/chemical.20recipes.20as.20functors/near/226271691\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Yes, I was going to add that Montanari and Meseguer consider this sort of morphism.  I didn't like it when I was trying to understand the category of Petri nets, because it's not the \"obvious\" or \"basic\" sort of map between Petri nets: it involves a mix of syntax and semantics.  But now that I understand <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2101.04238\">categories of nets</a>, I'm a lot more interested in this more general notion of morphism!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>For me it was the opposite. I wasn't interested in the morphisms we defined in categories of nets in the beginning because they weren't the right choice from a Petri net perspective, and ended up complicating my life a lot. Then I gave up and started using the most suitable from a categorical perspective. But I do agree that we could now characterize Petri net (bi?)simulations as extensions of nets, which would be a very cool thing to do</p>",
        "id": 226273802,
        "sender_full_name": "Fabrizio Genovese",
        "timestamp": 1613257306
    }
]